b"Have you noticed how much more email you get around this time of year? Scammers love to catch people out with fake offers. So don't open anything you didn't sign up for and watch out for emails or texts offering free gifts. Click on the link and you could end up with a computer virus. Delete anything that looks suspicious. And don't forget, if an offer looks too good to be true, it's probably a scam.

See link in bio to read up on how to protect yourself from the latest scams.

b'Send delivery scams packing! If you\xe2\x80\x99ve done your Christmas shopping online, you\xe2\x80\x99ll now be swamped with text and email delivery updates. But keep a close eye on them. Fake delivery notices are being reported by customers right now and we don\xe2\x80\x99t want anyone to be caught out. Please share this with loved ones who may not be on social media.

*What to look out for*
Any message stating a driver has tried to deliver your parcel and asking you to click a link to reschedule. Then, being asked to enter sensitive info like your date of birth, mobile number and card details. If you submit personal data, scammers could use it to call you up or access your bank account. 

*How to stay safe*
- Double and triple check delivery messages. 
- Make sure they link up to genuine orders. Does the message mention the goods you ordered or the company you ordered from?
- Check the message addresses you by name rather than just your email address or a basic \xe2\x80\x98Dear customer\xe2\x80\x99. 
- Look for tell-tale signs such as spelling and grammar mistakes.
- Don\xe2\x80\x99t submit any personal info like date of birth, card details or mobile number. Genuine delivery messages don\xe2\x80\x99t ask for this and don\xe2\x80\x99t ask for payment to re-deliver parcels.
- Delete anything dodgy, especially if you\xe2\x80\x99re not expecting a delivery, and if you\xe2\x80\x99re not sure, don\xe2\x80\x99t click the link. Delete the message and get in touch with the retailer you purchased from.

To stay up to date on the latest scams, see link in bio to check out our fraud guide.

Don't give away any personal or secure information on sites you're not sure about. And if anyone ever asks you for info such as bank login details, passcodes, card reader codes, remote access to your device or asks you to move money from your account, don't do it. It's a scam.

b'Bargain or fake? Apple AirPods, Xbox Series X, 4K TVs, the new iPhone 12\xe2\x80\xa6 wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t it be great to find a deal this Black Friday?\xc2\xa0

Just watch out for ads for fake goods on social media.\xc2\xa0They\xe2\x80\x99re not hard to spot when you know what to look for.

Firstly, if the deal looks too good to be true, it probably is. The second tactic scammers use is asking you to pay by direct bank transfer. That way, if they send you fake goods or nothing at all, they can just keep your money. And you lose it.

Stick to shopping on websites you know and trust and always pay by bank card, so you have some protection.

To\xc2\xa0keep yourself safe and\xc2\xa0stay up to date\xc2\xa0on\xc2\xa0the latest scams\xc2\xa0check out our fraud guide - see link in bio.

b"Grab a bargain but avoid scams and fakes this Black Friday. Here's how to stay safe shopping online:

Background checks
Do your research on the seller and check contact details on their website. Alarm bells should ring if there\xe2\x80\x99s no phone number or no physical address. Be aware that some sites may use a .co.uk web address, even if they\xe2\x80\x99re located abroad. If in doubt, don\xe2\x80\x99t shop there.

Your card is king
It\xe2\x80\x99s always safer to shop online using your debit or credit card. NEVER pay by\xc2\xa0bank transfer. Would you hand over cash to a stranger? No. It\xe2\x80\x99s the same with paying by bank transfer as you\xe2\x80\x99ll lose your money if something goes wrong. Be suspicious of anyone asking you to do that \xe2\x80\x93 it\xe2\x80\x99s a classic trick.

Keep your data safe
Don\xe2\x80\x99t give away any personal or secure information on websites you\xe2\x80\x99re not sure about. And if anyone ever asks for info such as bank login details, passcodes, card reader codes, remote access to your device or asks you to move money from your account, don\xe2\x80\x99t do it. It\xe2\x80\x99s a scam.

Beware of surprise emails
Have you noticed how many emails you get around Black Friday? Scammers love to catch people out with fake offers. So don\xe2\x80\x99t open anything you didn\xe2\x80\x99t sign up for and watch out for emails or texts offering free gifts. Click on the link and you could end up with a computer virus. Delete anything that looks suspicious.

See link in bio to visit our fraud guide for the latest info on staying safe online.

b'There\xe2\x80\x99s only one way to pay safely when you\xe2\x80\x99re shopping online and that\xe2\x80\x99s using your\xc2\xa0bank card.

It means we\xe2\x80\x99ve got your back if the worst happens. We can help if you\xe2\x80\x99ve paid for something that doesn\xe2\x80\x99t turn up, if there\xe2\x80\x99s a problem with it or if you\xe2\x80\x99ve been charged more than once, or the wrong amount.

Always look out for dodgy deals. A classic trick used by scammers is to ask people to pay by bank transfer. Never do this. If the price is too good to be true, chances are it\xe2\x80\x99s a fake. And if it is, you\xe2\x80\x99ll lose your money.

b'It\xe2\x80\x99s a chemical fact that spending makes us feel good*. So does shopping. That\xe2\x80\x99s  why it\xe2\x80\x99s called retail therapy. We get a buzz from it. Spending money when we\xe2\x80\x99re paying a lower than expected price can feel even better. But no one wants a spending hangover. So be logical; give yourself a little breathing space. You could turn off one-click spending altogether or put the item in your basket and hold off clicking pay for a bit. Then, ask yourself if you really need it. Is it worth it? Or would you rather put the money towards a longer-term goal?

b'Tempted to get cash out with your credit card when your bank balance is a little low? It could mean an unexpected fee.

It\xe2\x80\x99s called a cash advance fee and can be charged if you use your credit card in other situations too. For example:
- Gambling (including buying your lottery ticket online)
- Transferring money from your credit card into your bank account
- Topping up your mobile phone
- Buying foreign currency
- Paying your mortgage

Try to avoid these if you want to stop your credit card debt growing. 

If you\xe2\x80\x99re not sure when you might be charged for a certain type of payment, just ask. That\xe2\x80\x99s what we\xe2\x80\x99re here for. 

You can also find more helpful info on our website - see link in bio.

b"Are you worried you're gambling a little too much?
If you are, you can use our app to block payments to gambling sites.
\xc2\xa0
You're also not alone. Lockdown has seen some gamblers take more risks. Especially young people. In fact, according to the Gambling Commission, regular gamblers aged 18-34 are more likely than average to increase the time and money they spend on gambling. 

If you want help to slow down your gambling, you can block those payments on both your NatWest credit card and debit card. As soon as you switch off gambling in the app, you can't place any bets. And if you think you might be tempted and switch it back on straight away, there\xe2\x80\x99s a built-in 48-hour cooling-off period. This means you\xe2\x80\x99ll have to wait two days after unblocking before you gamble again. See link in bio for more info.

If you're concerned about your gambling, there are charities like GamCare that can help. There\xe2\x80\x99s also more on our website about how we can help if you\xe2\x80\x99re worried about gambling.

b'Avoiding unnecessary charges on your credit card is essential if you want to stop your debt growing. There\xe2\x80\x99s a \xc2\xa312 fee if you go \xc2\xa312 or more over your credit limit at any point during your monthly statement period. That could soon rack up if you let it happen a few times, even if you\xe2\x80\x99re only spending a little over your limit.

It\xe2\x80\x99s easy to keep tabs on how much you\xe2\x80\x99re spending. Check your credit card balance regularly in the mobile app and make sure we have an up to date mobile number for you. That way, we can text you as soon as you reach 95% of your credit limit. 

App eligibility criteria apply.

b'#WeWillRememberThem 
Today we join the rest of the UK in paying tribute to members of the Armed Services who have lost their lives serving their nation. We\xe2\x80\x99ll also be remembering our many fallen colleagues. 

John Garlett grew up in Catford, London and joined Westminster Bank aged 17. He was a keen rugby player and represented the bank in its rugby 1st XV for several seasons.  In July 1940, he left the bank for the Royal Navy, becoming a gunner. On 30th April 1941 he was part of the crew of Nerissa, a passenger steam ship carrying Canadian troops, among others, across the Atlantic.  The ship was struck and sunk by an enemy U boat. Able Seaman Garlett was among more than 200 passengers and crew killed. He was just 21 years old. His obituary in the bank\xe2\x80\x99s staff magazine noted, \xe2\x80\x98His loss is greatly felt at the branch, but his willingness at all times to do his bit, his happy spirit and cheerful disposition will be long remembered.\xe2\x80\x99 

If you have a relative who lost their life in WW1 or WW2 who used to work for one of our banks, you can find out more about them on our NatWest Group Remembers hub \xe2\x80\x93 see link in bio.

b'#WeWillRememberThem 
Many thousands of civilians had their lives tragically cut short during the two world wars, including our former colleague, Catherine Byland, who we\xe2\x80\x99d like to pay tribute to today.

Catherine was one of many women recruited into banking during the First World War to replace men who were away serving on the frontline. Most of these women left after Armistice, but Catherine stayed, becoming a long-serving member of staff at Reading branch, where she made many friends among the customers. 

It was around teatime on 10th February 1943 when a lone German plane dropped four bombs on the centre of Reading, killing 41 people and injuring many more. One of the dead was Catherine Byland. She was 47 years old. 

If you have a relative who lost their life in WW1 or WW2 who used to work for one of our banks, you can find out more about them on our NatWest Group Remembers hub \xe2\x80\x93 see link in bio.

b'#WeWillRememberThem
Today we join the rest of the UK in paying tribute to members of the Armed Services who have lost their lives serving their nation. We\xe2\x80\x99ll also be remembering our many fallen colleagues.

Seymour Gordon Duprey joined the Rye branch of London & County Bank (which went on to become part of NatWest) in 1906. As soon as war broke out in 1914 Seymour left to join the army, enlisting in October as a Private in the Inns of Court Officers Training Corps. A month later, he was commissioned into the Royal Naval Reserve and joined the crew of HMS Ramsey.  On 8th August 1915 the Ramsey was patrolling in the North Sea when she was torpedoed by a German minesweeper. She sank within four minutes, with the loss of 55 lives, including 28 year-old Assistant Paymaster Duprey. 

If you have a relative who lost their life in WW1 or WW2 who used to work for one of our banks, you can find out more about them on our NatWest Group Remembers hub \xe2\x80\x93 see link in bio.

b'Your card reader is an essential piece of kit when it comes to keeping your Online Banking secure. That\xe2\x80\x99s why scammers will do their best to try and convince you to part with its private codes. 

Read up on how they do it and you\xe2\x80\x99ll spot these scams from a mile off:

- Look out for someone calling saying they\xe2\x80\x99re from your bank, asking you about some unusual transactions. 
- They\xe2\x80\x99ll ask you to confirm your identity by giving the last 4 digits of your customer number and certain characters from your PIN or password.
- They\xe2\x80\x99ll then claim that you\xe2\x80\x99ve failed the security check but that you can be identified via the code on your card reader. 

Here\xe2\x80\x99s what\xe2\x80\x99s just been happening in the background:
The scammer has just used all the security details you just handed over to log into your Online Banking. Then they use the card reader code to set themselves up as a new payee so they can transfer your money into their account. 

Stay alert for calls like this and keep your card reader codes as safe as you keep your bank card PIN. Your bank would never call out of the blue and ask for them.

For more on staying safe from scams, see link in bio.

b'Planning a staycation this year instead of that big summer getaway? 

Then watch out for scams offering you deals on caravans and motorhomes that never turn up. You\xe2\x80\x99ll be offered a great discount, but the seller won\xe2\x80\x99t let you pick it up or view it due to \xe2\x80\x98\xe2\x80\x98lockdown restrictions\xe2\x80\x99\xe2\x80\x99. And after you\xe2\x80\x99ve transferred a deposit directly into the their account, you\xe2\x80\x99ll be left with no caravan and no holiday. 

Stay safe by looking out for: 
- Caravans and motorhomes at rock bottom prices 
- Sellers that won\xe2\x80\x99t show the item over video call 
- Requests to transfer money directly to someone selling online \xe2\x80\x93 you\xe2\x80\x99ll lose your money if it\xe2\x80\x99s a scam 
- Beware of links in payment request emails, it might take you to a fraudulent site

b'Calling all students: Think you\xe2\x80\x99ve found an easy way to fund your next laptop by letting someone use your bank account? Think again. 

Criminals are offering \xe2\x80\x9cquick, easy cash\xe2\x80\x9d for temporarily keeping money in their accounts.

Well, you\xe2\x80\x99d actually be involved in a criminal activity known as money muling. And if you\xe2\x80\x99re caught, your account will be closed, and you\xe2\x80\x99ll be blocked from other banks. It could even stop you from getting a student loan or a mobile phone contract.

b'Students, have you spotted a great deal on that last minute event?

As venues are reopening with social distancing in place, there may be high demand for limited spaces. Scammers could take advantage of you by posting fake tickets for popular student events.

How to stay safe:
- You should only buy from reputable ticket sites
- Watch out for emails offering tickets at bargain prices
- Pay by credit or debit card and NEVER transfer your money to someone directly to pay for tickets. You\xe2\x80\x99ll lose your money if it\xe2\x80\x99s a scam.

b'As the weather warms up scammers are trying to entice people to buy hot tubs online. They\xe2\x80\x99re listing fake ads promising great deals and asking people to pay the deposit directly into their account. Once you\xe2\x80\x99ve paid, they\xe2\x80\x99ll then claim the hot tub is on its way. But it\xe2\x80\x99ll never turn up, leaving you out of pocket. 

#TakeFive and remember:
- always use your credit or debit card when shopping online
- NEVER transfer money directly to anyone selling online, you will lose your money if it\xe2\x80\x99s a scam
- Stay safe by only buying from trusted sellers and secure websites.

b'Today our colleague Stacey, shares what Pride means to her.\n\n"For me it\xe2\x80\x99s the idea of community and extended family. Being of the generation where at 14 years old I became aware of my own sexuality and there wasn\xe2\x80\x99t really anything or anyone around to speak to. It could be very lonely and very isolating. So Pride reminds me that every year I never need to feel that alone again."'

b'Today our colleague Pasquale, shares what Pride means to him.\n\n"Pride is important to me because it connects to the rest of the queer community and its history. It reminds me that the path to equality is seriously challenging. It also reassures me about how much we\xe2\x80\x99ve achieved. Pride was born to fight a heteronormative societal standard that crushes the queer community. Today Pride connects people around the world, keeping the fight for justice alive."'

b'Today our colleague Sharniya, shares what Pride means to her.\n\n"Pride is important to me as an acknowledgement and celebration of the progress that\xe2\x80\x99s been made for the LGBTQ+ community. It\xe2\x80\x99s also a reminder that we need to continue fighting for progress so that we can attain true equality! #loveislove \xe2\x80\x9c'

b'Today our colleague Luke, shares what Pride means to him.\n\n"Pride allows everyone to be who they want to be no matter their background or where they\xe2\x80\x99ve come from. Personally, it allows me to be the best version of myself. We\xe2\x80\x99ll continue to march and celebrate until we are all equal. After all, we are all born naked and the rest is drag!"'

b'Today our colleague Orla, shares what Pride means to her.\n\n\xe2\x80\x9cPride is important to me because so many of us grow up sacrificing authenticity to feel safe. It is important to remember everything that\xe2\x80\x99s been done for us and everyone that\xe2\x80\x99s come before us as well as realising there is still a long road ahead before we are seen as equals and before we get the rights that we deserve.\xe2\x80\x9d'

b'Today our colleague Luke, shares what Pride means to him. \xe2\x80\x9cPride month this year is more important than ever. It gives us a chance to show we\xe2\x80\x99re still a community and we\xe2\x80\x99re still here to support each other. And most importantly, that we celebrate, even if you celebrate in a different way from normal. The main thing is to lift everyone\xe2\x80\x99s spirit, show we\xe2\x80\x99re still a community and show we\xe2\x80\x99re stronger together.\xe2\x80\x9d'

b'Today our colleague Ross, shares what Pride means to him. \xe2\x80\xa2 \xe2\x80\x9cPride is important for two reasons: Firstly, for us as LGBT+ individuals, it\xe2\x80\x99s a chance for us to come together as a community and support each other. And secondly, for our brothers and sisters around the world in places where it\xe2\x80\x99s not legal to be LGBT+ and can face very difficult consequences for who they are. We need to carry on the fight in the future and during COVID-19.\xe2\x80\x9d'

b"June is Pride Month and as it reaches its peak those celebrations are taking over our feed.  Over the next few days and into July, we'll be featuring colleagues from across the bank and finding out what Pride means to them. So many parades have been cancelled this year, but it doesn't mean that we can't show our support, Pride and solidarity with each other online."
